<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COCOA futures peaked at a new 40-month second position high of Pounds 983 a
tonne before slipping all the way back to close at Pounds 967 a tonne in the
near March position, Pounds 2 below Friday's level. Dealers said there was
no fresh news, people were just becoming more wary as the market approached
the psychologically significant Pounds 1,000. 'I think people believe it's
gone too far too fast,' one trader commented. The COFFEE market spent the
day trying to build a base following its recent correction and the January
contract closed at Dollars 1,173 a tonne, up Dollars 1, after trading
between Dollars 1,165 and Dollars 1,177. At the London Metal Exchange COPPER
prices edged off their lows, but still remained easier. News that Kennecott
workers at Bingham Canyon had reached a tentative agreement removed a
potential prop from the market as the three months position fell Dollars 10
to Dollars 1,690 a tonne. NICKEL trading slackened in the afternoon, with
the market paying less attention to the events in Moscow which had prompted
early firmness. The three months price closed at Dollars 4,170 a tonne, up
Dollars 57.50 on balance.
Compiled from Reuters
</TEXT>
