<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / International Company News: Lufthansa, UAL confirm agreement
on partnership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LUFTHANSA yesterday signed a wide-ranging commercial partnership with United
Airlines, the biggest US international carrier. The deal is expected to
intensify competition on international routes, especially across the north
Atlantic, and speed up the privatisation of the German national carrier.
Although the two sides said the agreement did not involve any equity swap,
they did not rule out eventual equity investments once Lufthansa was
privatised.
Lufthansa said the foundations for the United partnership had been laid by
the agreement reached 10 days ago between Germany and the US on a new
bilateral air pact between the two countries.
'The new aviation agreement and the co-operative alliance between Lufthansa
and United are important prerequisites for early moves towards Lufthansa's
privatisation,' the German airline added.
The partnership with United would help reduce Lufthansa's heavy losses on
the north Atlantic and return the company into the black, Mr Jurgen Weber,
Lufthansa's chairman, said. The German airline, which has embarked on a
restructuring programme, expects to halve its annual losses this year
compared to 1992. Lufthansa said it may return to profitability in 1994. It
posted a 1992 group net loss of DM391m (Dollars 230m).
The company said that it had eliminated 5,500 jobs by last June and it
expected to cut another 2,900 jobs by the beginning of 1994. The
Lufthansa-United deal is primarily designed to increase the two airlines'
worldwide revenues, but the two carriers expect it to provide cost-cutting
opportunities.
Mr Weber hoped the United deal would help swing Austrian Airlines to
co-operate with Lufthansa rather than join the European four-airline merger
being negotiated between SAS, KLM, Swissair and Austrian.
The Austrian carrier is expected to decide later this month whether to opt
for Lufthansa or for the four-airline merger. The Lufthansa-United deal and
the proposed four-airline merger reflect the scramble for alliances and
partnerships engulfing an industry facing growing deregulation and
increasingly global competition.
The United alliance is likely to face stiff opposition from American
Airlines and Delta Air Lines, the two other big US carriers. American had
sought to negotiate a deal with Lufthansa and is the only big US carrier
without a leading European partner.
Delta, which has equity links with Swissair, sees its position as the
biggest US carrier at Frankfurt threatened by yesterday's deal.
However, Mr Stephen Wolf, United's chairman, said he was confident the
agreement would win the necessary US government approval.
</TEXT>
