<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / UK Company News: Standard Chartered action
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Standard Chartered, the UK bank, has received Pounds 25.9m in a settlement
of its legal action against the National Housing Bank of India.
The claim was one of several against banks and financial institutions by
Standard Chartered following irregularities in the Bombay securities market
in 1991 and 1992. The bank disclosed in March that it had sustained a Pounds
305m loss on Indian operations last year and it raised its provision for
possible bad debts resulting from the Bombay securities trading scandal to
Pounds 272m. Mr Malcolm Williamson, chief executive, said: 'We are very
pleased that (we) have been able to settle this outstanding claim in a
sensible commercial manner. We shall continue to pursue our claims with
other counterparties and hope that they will respond as positively and
constructively as the National Housing Bank'.
In November, ANZ Grindlays Bank, the Australian-owned group involved in the
Bombay securities scandal, paid Rs5.06bn (Pounds 116m) to National Housing
Bank against seven disputed cheques.
