<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Geneticists have just identified the learning gene which brings a little
nearer the day when it may be possible to ask the doctor to make your child
a Kasparov. Public awareness of genetic engineering, both its possibilities
and the attendant ethical dilemmas, is growing fast. Cracking the Code (BBC
2, 9.30), the series devoted to genetic engineering, strikes me as something
of a missed opportunity.
Cracking the Code is worthwhile and its American presenter, Dr David Suzuki,
is a good communicator. However, it tends to underestimate viewers'
sophistication and at times even a layman has the feeling that it is out of
date. Furthermore, it is irritating to find yet another medical series which
concentrates on the North American picture.
If you found last week's two-hour opening instalment of Armistead Maupin's
Tales of the City (C4, 10.00) slow and insipid, I would agree. However, this
series does build up momentum as it goes along. Strongly in its favour is
Olympia Dukakis's performance as the surprising Mrs Madrigal, enchanting
enough to make it worth it.
</TEXT>
