<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: The flamboyant tendency
breaks cover - Alison Smith catches Euro-sceptic MP and author Teresa Gorman
in conciliatory mood . . . almost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LAUNCH of Mrs Teresa Gorman's book about the 'dirty tricks' endured by
Tory Euro-rebels, coincided almost to the minute with the insistence from
Sir Norman Fowler, party chairman, that it was time to draw a line under the
troubles and divisions of the past year.
But while Mrs Gorman publicised her book The Bastards, by re-opening
Maastricht wounds there was some evidence in what she said to support Sir
Norman's assertion.
The paper being carefully pasted over the cracks may just be strong enough
to last the week.
Mrs Gorman maintained a severely Euro-sceptic line, but said only that it
was 'still an open matter' whether she would vote against the government the
next time the vexed question of value added tax on domestic fuel came before
the Commons.
She appeared to accept that VAT on fuel would be implemented, and that the
point of continuing to exert pressure was to make ministers think carefully
before extending VAT further - in which she would probably be in the
mainstream of party opinion.
Her tone on Mr John Major's leadership has also been tempered since the
summer.
In August there were dark hints that unless the prime minister changed his
policies then the party would change him. Yesterday Mrs Gorman said: 'I
believe at the moment it would be completely inappropriate to change the
leader.'
While her remarks remained somewhat barbed, she said that her purpose was
'to support John Major but to try and change his mind'.
Mrs Gorman's role as standard-bearer for the flamboyant tendency among the
persistent rebels, makes her softening of tone especially good news for
party managers, in spite of the minor controversy over whether the
conference bookstall would stock her book.
But her words echoed the views of one party official that although
Maastricht was a real battle, VAT on fuel is not an issue over which the
party will tear itself apart.
Certainly the first representatives arriving at the Imperial, the conference
hotel, seemed keen to avoid a public fight with the party leadership.
In the bar and lounge they expressed irritation and dismay at the way in
which the VAT issue had been handled, but sounded similarly disenchanted at
the way some former ministers were adding to the government's difficulties.
Some also believe that distaste for the media will serve the party well,
with many representatives determined to deny the press a week of fireworks
in the conference hall. 'There'll be headbangers on the fringe, and the
representatives will give us a kicking in private,' one party worker said,
'but they'll want a good conference'.
An MP with a large enough majority to be relatively detached expressed a
similar view.
'You won't get a true and fair picture this week,' he said, 'what happens
over the next few months is going to be much more important.'
</TEXT>
