FT  05 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: MacGregor warned over BR
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MacGregor, the transport secretary, should 'bow to common sense and
travellers' wishes' and abandon rail privatisation, a passenger group urged
yesterday, on the eve of his address to the conference.
Opinion polls showed only 8 per cent of people believed privatisation would
work, said Mr Steve Wilkinson, chairman of the Railway Development Society.
He said there was 'precious little enthusiasm for privatisation among Mr
MacGregor's parliamentary colleagues, party members or, indeed, potential
private railway operators'.
Meanwhile, Mr Brian Wilson, a Labour transport spokesman, warned that 23
Tory marginal seats could be at risk if the 'running down' of the
cash-starved London-to-Scotland West Coast main line was allowed to
continue.
Fares would rise by up to 50 per cent and staff levels would be cut by more
than A third, the Scottish Save Our Railways campaign said yesterday. Its
figures were based on a study carried out by the Scottish Transport Studies
Group.
ScotRail is to be one of the first pilot shadow franchise areas, a test for
privatisation.
Meanwhile British Rail said yesterday that an increasing number of speed
restrictions are having to be imposed on lines because of lack of
maintenance funds.
BR warned: 'We need Pounds 850m a year just to keep existing passenger
services at their present level and our funding for each of the next three
years is less than that.'
The environmental group Transport 2000 said it feared routes in need of
repair might be axed altogether when BR is privatised.
