<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Tories row over veto on
speakers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BEHIND-THE-SCENES row over attempts by the organisers to stifle attacks on
Mr John Major's government erupted last night on the eve of the
Conservatives' Blackpool conference.
Officers of the party's National Union were accused of seeking to 'screen
out' representatives planning critical speeches from the conference floor
during this week's debates.
The task of vetoing potentially 'dangerous' speakers has been handed to
ministers' political advisers and to the research department at Conservative
central office.
But a number of ministers have expressed fears that the tactic could
backfire by increasing the anger of the government's critics and provoking
public demonstrations during debates. They have told their advisers to
ensure a reasonable balance in the choice of speakers.
The conference organisers are also trying to ensure that the prime
minister's critics on the Tory back benches at Westminster - the so-called
'barmies' - are denied a voice by preventing all MPs from speaking in the
main debates.
All of the constituency party motions chosen by the organisers are
supportive of the government's policies.
The motions range from one on the economy urging the government to stick
with its policies, to one praising the government's intention to target
social security benefits.
There is no mention of the imposition of value added tax on fuel or of the
government's inability to curb rising crime rates, despite the scores of
critical motions submitted.
But to the embarrassment even of some cabinet ministers, the organisers have
attempted to prevent any public rows by 'vetting' those constituency
activists who have asked to speak.
The principal flashpoints at this week's conference are judged to be
tomorrow's law and order debate and Thursday's economic debate.
But there are also fears that the opponents of the Maastricht treaty could
seek to stage a demonstration during today's foreign affairs debate.
Sir Basil Feldman, the chairman of the National Union, denied yesterday that
the organisers' refusal to hold a separate debate on VAT was an attempt to
stifle debate.
He said that the issue was certain to be raised from the floor during the
economy debate.
But in a reflection of the determination in Blackpool to damp down attacks
both on the government and Mr Major's leadership, Sir Basil told a press
conference: 'The party is fed up with the disloyalty and negative messages
being put out by the malcontent minority.'
</TEXT>
