<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / Gloomy forecast for construction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION in the construction industry is set to continue, more jobs
will go and sustained recovery is not expected until 1995, a forecast
yesterday from the Building Employers Confederation says.
The confederation's autumn state-of-trade inquiry, based on a poll of 600
companies, found that only a third of companies were confident of an
increase in output over the next 12 months, with the rest predicting a
decline or at best no change.
A fifth of companies expect to reduce their workforce still further over the
next few months. Employment in the industry has fallen by more than 500,000
since the middle of 1989 - the present recession is now the longest in the
industry since the 1930s.
Sir Brian Hill, the confederation's president, said: 'The construction
recession is still continuing and it must be worrying that the majority of
firms do not expect any improvement in output over the next 12 months. This
will postpone any sustained recovery until 1995.
'This must also mean that unemployment levels will remain high over the same
period, which in turn will further damage the industry's training and
recruitment programmes.'
The survey's findings are in line with recent industry forecasts of a
further 2 per cent fall in construction industry output this year, making a
total fall of about 17 per cent over the past three years.
However, the confederation said more companies reported an increase in
third-quarter output, compared with the second quarter. Work inquiries had
also improved, albeit only slightly and from a low base.
The survey found that the housing market had shown some improvement from
last year, but was still a long way from recovery.
The confederation said fears of redundancy and uncertainties about possible
tax changes in the November Budget continued to undermine buyers'
confidence.
In the private commercial sector the level of inquiries had again fallen
sharply.
In the private industrial sector, growth prospects had improved in line with
those in the manufacturing sector. But because of the time lag between
output and investment, a large revival is considered unlikely unless Budget
measures are introduced to bring forward investment. The repair and
maintenance market showed signs of improving.
The confederation said output improved among companies in the south,
south-west, north and north-west but fell in London, the Midlands and the
Yorkshire region.
State of Trade Inquiry. BEC Publications, Federation House, 2309/11 Coventry
Road, Sheldon, Birmingham B26 3PL. Pounds 50 a year, Pounds 15 for single
quarterly issue.
</TEXT>
