FT  05 OCT 93 / Exhibition opens in London on improving Communication for
people with disabilities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROFESSOR Stephen Hawking, the Cambridge University cosmologist, yesterday
joined schoolboy Neil Wallace at the opening of a Science Museum exhibition
in London on improving communication for people with disabilities, Clive
Cookson writes.
Prof Hawking, who has motor neurone disease, communicates via a computerised
speech synthesiser with a special keyboard operated by two fingers of his
left hand, and can manage about 15 words a minute.
Neil, 10, has cerebral palsy. He is using the US-made Liberator, which in
its basic form costs Pounds 5,795. Prof Hawking said such devices made such
a difference to the lives of people who could not speak that they should be
available on the National Health Service.
