<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / MoD rejects call for more orders to save BAe jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MINISTRY of Defence has told Ayrshire MPs that it will not order
aircraft specially to avert redundancies at British Aerospace's Jetstream
subsidiary at Prestwick.
The plant, which employs 2,500 people making Jetstream turbo-prop regional
airliners, is expected to announce a package of redundancies in the next few
weeks because of a shortage of orders.
It has already told its workforce that it will have to realign production
programmes with market demand.
Mr George Foulkes, Labour MP for Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley, together
with four other Ayrshire Labour MPs, had urged the MoD to bring forward
replacement of 26 Jetstream aircraft used by the RAF and the navy, and also
to replace the RAF's Andover aircraft with Jetstreams.
But Mr Jonathan Aitken, defence minister, has told Mr Foulkes that the
Jetstream fleet will not be replaced in the short or medium-term. The
Andovers are being replaced with existing aircraft and commercial charters.
Mr Allan MacDonald, Jetstream's managing director, told the workforce in
August that all manufacturers of aircraft in Jetstream's regional category
were facing severe shortages of orders and were making heavy discounts on
prices.
Yesterday Mr MacDonald told employees that the main board of British
Aerospace and the Prestwick management would be meeting on October 13 and an
announcement would be made soon after.
He added that a final decision on the cost-cutting package had been delayed
because of the need to investigate more options. In August he had promised a
decision by the end of the month.
The company makes the 19-seat Jetstream 31 and the 29-seat Jetstream 41. It
is also building the first Jetstream ATP (advance turbo-prop) aircraft after
production of this model was transferred from Woodford near Manchester.
</TEXT>
