<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / Amerada Hess to shed 10% of staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMERADA HESS, the US oil company whose North Sea operations have expanded
rapidly in recent years, is to cut about 10 per cent of its 1,000-strong UK
workforce today.
The staff cuts are thought to be confined to onshore workers and are not
expected to affect employees on North Sea production rigs.
The company has blamed the cuts on changes to the Petroleum Revenue Tax
introduced by the government in the last Budget. Other factors cited by the
company include the present low oil prices and the fact that the prospect of
further large-scale oil discoveries in the North Sea is becoming more
remote.
The cut marks an end to Amerada's aggressive expansion of its British
operations in recent years. It spent more than Dollars 800m (Pounds 519m) to
develop the Scott field, which was brought onstream last month recently and
is likely to be one of the largest developments on the UK continental shelf
in the 1990s.
Amerada has made no secret of its opposition to the tax changes proposed by
Mr Norman Lamont, the former chancellor of the exchequer, in his Budget
speech last March. The company's biggest concern, shared by a number of
smaller oil companies operating in the North Sea, was that exploration costs
could no longer be offset against the tax.
The company has repeatedly warned in recent months that it would have to
re-assess its exploration programme in the UK.
It said that the tax reforms reduced the incentive for companies to seek out
the smaller reserves of oil which are likely to characterise UK offshore
exploration in coming years.
Mr Sam Laidlow, managing director of Amerada's UK operations, predicted
earlier this year that job cuts would follow the introduction of the new tax
system.
The government's reforms included a lowering of the tax rate on existing
fields and its elimination on new fields.
The effect of the changes was to make production from developed fields more
profitable but to increase sharply the cost of exploration for companies
that had been able to take advantage of the tax offset.
Almost 160 jobs are to be created by Avon Rubber, the tyre and motor parts
company, in a Pounds 3m investment to produce components for vehicle air
conditioning systems near Williamstown, Rhondda, south Wales.
</TEXT>
