<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / BT to cut 1,187 operator jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Telecommunications is to shut 10 of its 29 telephone operator
centres with the loss of 1,187 jobs.
The company said some of the job cuts were included in last year's
announcement of a plan to cut 30,000 jobs over the two years to March 1995.
About 8,000 operators, mainly working on directory inquiries, will be left
after the latest cuts. But BT said last night that the company had not ruled
out further job losses.
Mr Alan Johnson, general secretary of the Union of Communication Workers,
said last night that the news came as a 'devastating blow'. He added: 'These
closures are on a far greater scale than we could possibly have expected.'
BT said the company hoped to achieve the staff reduction through
non-replacement and redeployment, without having to resort to any compulsory
redundancies.
It added that the main reason for the cuts in the number of centres stemmed
from the decline in the number of calls being made by customers needing
help.
The union claims this is because BT now charges for this service but the
company believes the decline in demand stems partly from improvements in the
telephone network and from the greater use of pay phones.
The centres to be closed are at Chester, Edinburgh, Exeter, Glasgow,
Kettering, Leeds, Norwich, Sheffield, Southampton and Taunton.
The latest job cuts are likely to intensify the dangers of industrial
disruption this autumn, union officials claimed.
The union is already urging all BT operators to support calls for a strike
ballot in preparation for industrial action.
This is in protest at planned cuts in operators' allowances and benefits. A
union conference is planned for next week where delegates are expected to
endorse the leadership's strike call by agreeing to the calling of a ballot.
Mr Johnson said that the union was concerned that the rundown in the number
of the operator centres would reduce the quality of BT's service to the
customer.
Last month it was revealed that BT may move as many as 18,000 office jobs
out of central London under a relocation strategy being considered by an
internal review team. The move would leave only about 2,000 posts in central
London.
The relocation is aimed at rationalising BT's substantial office holdings
and could save the company up to Pounds 44m in London-weighting payments.
</TEXT>
