<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / Growth in national skills training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYERS' awareness of vocational qualifications has risen significantly
over the past few years, although only a third of employers are offering
these work-based qualifications, a survey funded by the Department of
Employment has found, Lisa Wood writes.
Skill Needs in Britain is the fourth in an annual series examining
recruitment difficulties and other skills and training issues among
companies that employ more than 25 people.
The first National Vocational Qualifications (NVQs) were introduced in
mid-1987 but they have been slow to arrive in the workplace. Employers have
often complained about their cost and quality.
The survey showed that 74 per cent of employers knew about NVQs, compared
with 63 per cent in 1992. Only 33 per cent of employers said they offered
them to employees. Four out of five of these employers were satisfied with
the qualifications on offer.
The main reason for not offering NVQs was a lack of detailed knowledge of
what they involved.
Skill Needs in Britain. IFF Research, 26 Whiskin Street, London EC1R OBP.
Pounds 40.
</TEXT>
