<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / Government cuts school reports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TEACHERS were yesterday offered deep cuts in the number of reports they must
make to parents under the national curriculum as the government tried to
persuade unions to abandon their boycott of school tests.
Reactions from the three teachers' unions that boycotted the tests earlier
this year were lukewarm. None were prepared to call off their action. There
were, however, signs of disagreement.
For 14-year-olds, teachers must now only report on six items of national
curriculum assessment for each pupil, rather than 41, while for
seven-year-olds, the number of items has been cut from 22 to 13.
Schools would have to give each child's parents at least one written report
a year, but its time of publication would be flexible. Pupils' results would
be compared with the average for their year-group.
Baroness Blatch, the education minister, called on teachers to end their
boycott.
The National Union of Teachers said Baroness Blatch 'appeared to have
misunderstood the union's concerns'.
It said: 'The tests continue to be educationally unsound. They may not match
teacher assessments, which will result in misleading information being given
to parents.'
But the National Association of Schoolmasters/Union of Women Teachers, whose
boycott is based on its complaint against excessive workload, welcomed the
proposals. The union's executive meets at the end of this week and will
consider the government's proposals 'very seriously'.
The Association of Teachers and Lecturers said the government had made a
'move in the right direction'. It would re-ballot members once it had
evidence on the changes the government would make to workload.
</TEXT>
