<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Security Council yesterday extended by six months the mandate of UN
troops in the former Yugoslavia and tenuously linked the lifting of
sanctions against Belgrade to enactment of a peace plan in Croatia, Reuter
reports from New York.
The resolution was adopted by a unanimous vote, including Russia which had
previously objected to the measures. The Council warned nations of 'serious
consequences' if they interfered in Croatia, a reference to any military
supplies Belgrade might deliver to fellow Serbs.
Meanwhile, fresh clashes erupted in north-west Bosnia yesterday after forces
loyal to local Moslem leader Fikret Abdic tried to wrest control of Bosnian
army positions in the isolated Bihac region.
