<PROFILE>_AN-DJEC1AAMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931005
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 93 / Sweden plans big company tax package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SWEDEN'S centre-right government yesterday announced a big package of
corporate tax reforms designed to encourage business expansion and lower a
record 13 per cent unemployment rate.
Under the proposals, to be put to parliament later this month, the basic
rate of corporate tax will fall 2 points to 28 per cent, taxes on dividends
from Swedish companies will be scrapped for Swedish residents, and capital
gains tax on equities will be halved to 12.5 per cent. Tax rules for small
non-incorporated businesses will also change to bring about lower rates on
capital yields and retained profits.
'The idea is to make it profitable to expand businesses and to start new
businesses,' said Mr Bo Lundgren, deputy finance minister. 'We are taking
away obstacles to growth.'
With the budget deficit set to rise next year to 15 per cent of gross
domestic product, the changes are to be fully financed. Just over half the
SKr3.3bn (Pounds 273m) cost of the tax cuts - to take effect from next
January - has already been accounted for in the 1993-94 budget. The balance
will be financed mainly by raising employer contributions from 30 per cent
of employees' salary to 30.2 per cent and partly by cuts in individual tax
allowances for days spent working abroad.
The package is the most far-reaching change in the corporate tax regime
since 1991 when the then Social Democratic government cut the basic
corporate tax rate from 52 per cent to 30 and largely dismantled an
elaborate system of tax write-offs.
The Social Democrats, now in opposition, persuaded the present government
last year to postpone the reforms because of the severe pressure the
recession has placed on welfare programmes. But Mr Lundgren said he was
confident parliament would approve the proposals.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SEZ   Sweden, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
