<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 93 / Fiat holds talks on European alliances to cut costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN and PETER MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR GIANNI AGNELLI, the Fiat chairman, said his company had been discussing
possible alliances with other European car-markers to tackle overcapacity
and high production costs.
Though nothing had come of these talks, he said further significant
consolidation of the European car business was inevitable. It would perhaps
be triggered by one of the bigger manufacturers drawing clearly ahead of the
rest.
Mr Agnelli would not identify companies with which Fiat might co-operate.
But he said that 'in Europe, there are too many brands. I think we need to
reduce them'. He explained: 'If something happens, and one producer rises to
24 per cent of the market, then the whole thing starts moving.' The European
car market is split between six main producers, with Volkswagen, the
biggest, accounting for about 17 per cent.
Fiat last week announced a L966bn (Pounds 400m) net loss for the first half
of 1993, caused by the steep fall in demand for cars in Europe.
Fiat, which last week launched Italy's biggest rights issue, also said it
would sell its 58 per cent stake in La Rinascente, Italy's biggest retailing
group, to generate additional funds. Ifil, the quoted investment company
dominated by Agnelli family interests, is a likely buyer. The disposal is
likely to generate an extraordinary gain of L437bn.
Mr Agnelli added that the need for austerity would put pressure on Fiat's
ability to pay a dividend. Stressing that a decision was still up to the
board next May, he hoped it would at least be possible to pay holders of
Fiat's non-voting savings stock.
