<DATE>931004
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 93 / Stiffer parking fines for London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOTORISTS who park illegally in any of three London boroughs face stiffer
penalties from today under parking laws due to spread throughout the capital
over the next 10 months.
Hammersmith and Fulham, Bromley and Lewisham have taken over routine parking
enforcement from the police by becoming 'special parking areas'. The
boroughs will employ their own parking attendants who will be able to issue
a new type of ticket known as penalty charge notices. These carry a fine of
Pounds 30 to Pounds 60 depending on the area. There will be a 50 per cent
discount for motorists who pay within 14 days.
Persistent offenders with outstanding fines will be clamped - and from next
year will not be released until they have paid what they owe. The declamping
fee will be Pounds 38. Where illegal parking obstructs traffic, cars will be
towed away rather than clamped.
Revenue from the scheme will go to the local authority which can use it to
cover the cost of the scheme, provide extra parking and improve public
transport.
</TEXT>
