<TEXT>
JAGUAR, the luxury carmaker, is to enter the Chinese market with the aim of
establishing a network of distribution and service centres in cities
throughout the country, Kevin Done writes.
The company , a subsidiary of Ford of the US, is appointing Inchcape, the
UK-based international services and marketing group, as its exclusive
importer/distributor for China. Inchape is the Jaguar importer/distributor
for Hong Kong, the carmaker's fastest-growing market, and for Macao.
Jaguar China is to be set up as a division of Inchcape Pacific with the aim
of starting Jaguar sales in China before the end of the year.
Mr Nick Scheele, Jaguar chairman and chief executive, said that China was
set to become one of the company's most important development markets.
Jaguar said that it expected to sell 40 cars in China this year rising to
100 in 1994.
