FT  04 OCT 93 / Union to serve ambulance writ
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORTHUMBRIA Ambulance Service will today be served with a High Court writ by
Unison, the public-sector union, challenging alleged increases in working
hours without extra pay for some ambulance staff.
The writ claims the ambulance service, which covers Tyne and Wear and
Northumberland, breached National Health Service agreements by unilaterally
trying to change working hours for 37 staff.
The service, which was one of the first to become an NHS trust, said it
could not comment as it had not received the writ.
The legal move is the latest in an increasingly acrimonious battle between
Unison, backed by Labour MPs, and Mr Laurie Caple, chief executive of the
trust.
Critics have attacked Mr Caple over his income-generation schemes, which
range from car servicing to security advice, and his management style.
Mr Jonathan Upton, a Unison official, said: 'This latest imposition of
increased hours for no pay is an attempt to recoup money lost on speculative
commercial ventures from the pockets of dedicated ambulance workers.'
The trust's 1992-93 report shows the schemes making a net surplus of Pounds
14,857, but critics argue the Pounds 30,000 fee paid to an agent in the
United Arab Emirates to promote its services should be deducted from this
figure.
