<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 93 / Tories look at rules on leadership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POWERFUL 1922 Committee of Conservative backbenchers is to consider
Baroness Thatcher's suggestions for changing the rules governing Tory
leadership contests as a matter of priority.
Dame Jill Knight, the vice-chairman of the 1922 executive, said last night
she was sure the committee would look at the issues raised by Lady Thatcher
'as soon as possible'.
But she indicated there was probably not enough time to head off a possible
leadership challenge to Mr John Major, the prime minister, this autumn by
rewriting the rules in line with Lady Thatcher's proposal.
'I would imagine it would be too late to alter the rules for this year,'
Dame Jill, the MP for Birmingham Edgbaston, said.
Lady Thatcher told The Sunday Times yesterday that existing rules for
determining when a leader could be challenged should be discontinued during
periods when the Conservatives were in government.
The former prime minister said: 'I do not think the prime ministership of a
nation should be determined by some leadership rules that were fashioned for
being in opposition.
'I think the existence of them can actually destabilise the government of
the day - the party really must think again.
'I think they must think about this very carefully and ponder very deeply on
whether an election for the leader of the party should apply during a time
when that leader is also prime minister.'
Under current rules - modified in 1991 as a result of Lady Thatcher's own
removal as leader - a leadership contest could be triggered if 34
Conservative MPs wrote to Sir Marcus Fox, chairman of the 1922, within 14
days of the start of a new parliamentary session to say such a step was
warranted.
Sir Norman Fowler, the party chairman, yesterday welcomed Lady Thatcher's
proposals, saying he was 'very much in favour of the sort of changes she is
suggesting'.
But the response of members of the 1922 executive was mixed. Dame Jill said
Lady Thatcher had a 'strong point' in asserting that a sitting prime
minister was different from a leader of the opposition. But Sir Marcus said
he was wary of the proposals.
Another senior member of the executive said the proposed change would not
help Mr Major since it would be seen as a sign of weakness.
The 1991 rule change had 'tipped the balance rather against stalking horse
candidates anyway,' he said.
</TEXT>
