<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 93 / Arguments over taxation rage among rivals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ARGUMENT over tax and spending reached a new pitch yesterday as the
leading Tory protagonists fired their final salvoes before this week's party
conference in Blackpool.
With the government's plans to extend value added tax to domestic fuel
expected to be attacked by some grassroots representatives, Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor, said his predecessor Mr Norman Lamont had been quite
right to include the measure in his last Budget package.
Mr Clarke, writing in the Conservative party newspaper Newsline, said the
'British habit' of zero-rating many goods had created anomalies in what was
'otherwise a fair tax'. But he did not rule out changing Mr Lamont's
proposals by levying VAT at a lower rate than 17.5 per cent.
The chancellor - who will address conference under the watchful gaze of
Baroness Thatcher, the former prime minister, on Thursday - urged the
government's critics to hold their fire until the package of measures to
help the less well-off pay their fuel bills was unveiled.
But he sought to lower expectations of what this package would include,
saying that increased benefit payments 'already exceed the extra costs on
VAT on fuel' for some households.
'There is no reason at all why the better off should not pay VAT on their
central heating,' he said.
Among the government's right-wing critics, the Thatcherite Conservative Way
Forward yesterday advised Mr John Major, the prime minister, that a pledge
not to increase income tax in next month's Budget would 'work wonders for
party morale'.
Mr Lamont was also on the attack, saying it would be 'wrong if all the
contribution to deficit reduction came from increased taxes'.
'We were not re-elected to raise taxes and action must be taken on
spending,' he told CWF's quarterly magazine.
Contradicting a number of cabinet ministers who have argued that next year's
public expenditure could not be reduced below existing pre-set levels, he
said there was 'nothing sacrosanct' about the 'tight' spending targets
agreed under his chancellorship.
'Action in the first instance ought to be on the spending side,' he said.
Mr Michael Portillo, the Thatcherite Treasury chief secretary, spoke of the
need to 'minimise the size of the state', in an article for CWF focusing on
the longer term.
'The government spends too much of the citizens' money,' he argued. 'Too
large a proportion of government spending will lead to an oppressive level
of taxation . . . Borrowing merely shifts the burden to a future
generation,' he said.
Lord Tebbit, the former Tory chairman, said tax increases were inevitable
because of the need to get the deficit down and the government's
determination not to cut public expenditure below pre-set levels.
</TEXT>
