<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 93 / Health trusts cautious on deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY a fifth of National Health Service trusts have introduced some form
of local pay for small groups of workers, such as cleaners and healthcare
assistants, according to an internal government review recently issued to
health authorities.
The report is the first by the NHS Management Executive on how the 154 first
and second-wave NHS trusts have exercised their new powers over pay and
conditions. Trusts have the power to develop local pay and conditions
packages for new staff although staff who transferred into trusts are
entitled to keep the central arrangements of the Whitley Councils and the
pay-review bodies.
Trusts have been cautious in moving towards local packages, particularly as
many want to do full job evaluations of all their staff first. The report
shows a higher than previously assessed number of trusts moving towards
local packages. It is likely that the chancellor's demand that total wage
bills in the public sector must be frozen next year, and that all pay
increases must be funded by productivity gains, will lead to an acceleration
of local pay arrangements within trusts.
According to the government's Human Resource Survey 18.5 per cent of
respondents had introduced some form of local pay, but this was mainly for
small or self-contained groups such as cleaners, healthcare assistants and
senior managers. A further 33 per cent said they intended to introduce it in
some parts of their organisations in one to two years.
Ambulance services were the most advanced in moving towards local pay and
conditions, accounting for four of the eight trusts which had comprehensive
local pay and reward schemes in place.
Northumbria Ambulance Service will today be served with a High Court writ by
Unison, the public-sector union, challenging alleged increases in hours
without extra pay for some ambulance staff.
</TEXT>
