<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 93 / Conference minefield for Major: David Owen on pitfalls for
the prime minister this week at Blackpool
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFERENCE'S first full day on Tuesday could start uncomfortably, with the
spotlight firmly on Europe, the issue at the heart of the party's civil war.
Tension is unavoidable no matter how soothingly foreign secretary Douglas
Hurd urges the party to come together.
Mr Major's main headaches will not be confined to the hall. On the fringe,
Euro-sceptics Bill Cash, Nicholas Budgen, Richard Shepherd and Teresa Gorman
will all be in action, with Mr Cash launching a new Euro-sceptic
secretariat: the European Foundation.
Lord Tebbit's first appearance of three, at a lunchtime meeting organised by
the Thatcherite Conservative Way Forward, may produce more problematical
headlines.
Tuesday is also railway day - when transport secretary John MacGregor may be
called to account over the controversial rail privatisation plans.
WEDNESDAY
THIS could be Mr Major's most comfortable day. His main misfortune is to be
deprived of the incapacitated Michael Heseltine to rally the troops before
lunch.
There may be troubling moments over the government's plans for pensions, tax
and public spending in the debate addressed by Peter Lilley, the rightwing
social security secretary.
On the fringe, the shadow of James Molyneaux, the Ulster Unionist leader,
could haunt Mr Major. It is still not clear what, if anything, the Unionists
expect in return for supporting the government in July in a crucial
Maastricht vote.
The right-left divisions in the party could be highlighted again by Lord
Tebbit who will talk to the right-wing Selsdon Group, while two right-wing
ministers - Neil Hamilton and Michael Forsyth - will be closely listened to
for wayward words when they address Conservative Way Forward.
John Biffen, the respected former cabinet minister who is known for speaking
his mind, might set the cat among the pigeons at another fringe debate as
might Christopher Gill, a Euro-sceptic leader.
THURSDAY
PROMISES to be the trickiest day so far.
No sooner will chancellor Kenneth Clarke have sat down after replying to a
debate likely to include calls to rethink plans for VAT on fuel and rule out
Budget tax increases altogether, than Norman Lamont, his predecessor, will
be on his feet and possibly on the attack.
Mr Lamont's appearance is the fringe event the leadership is most fearing,
after the former chancellor's criticism of government policy.
Baroness Thatcher will also visit the conference, to an adoring welcome from
many of the faithful, with her memoirs waiting in the wings.
Michael Portillo, the rising star of the right, in fringe appearances on
Wednesday and Thursday is expected to map out his agenda on Europe and
public spending, which may be different in tone and substance from that of
the prime minister.
The evening will end with a bust-up to savour: Kenneth Clarke goes
head-to-head against Lord Tebbit in a Sunday Telegraph-sponsored debate on
the future of Conservatism.
FRIDAY
THE prime minister's big day.
After the divisions of the week over Europe, tax, and the welfare state, Mr
Major must give the speech of his life to save his leadership.
The prime minister - who is planning to speak without an autocue - is
expected to focus on enduring Conservative values such as living within your
means and law and order.
He is not expected to try to modify his pedestrian style; it is unlikely
there will be any rabble rousing.
A dutiful standing ovation is guaranteed. But what matters is what the
faithful will mutter about his efforts as they munch their sandwiches on the
trains home.
</TEXT>
