<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 93 / Ministers hint at retreat over BR franchise bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday signalled the possibility of a retreat over its
plans to exclude British Rail from bidding for passenger franchises once
privatisation of the network is under way.
Ministers acknowledged that it might now prove impossible to overturn in the
House of Commons an amendment passed by the Lords allowing BR to bid for
franchises. More than a dozen Conservative MPs had indicated they were
determined to support the amendment, wiping out the government's majority
among MPs.
But ministers are to explore at this week's Conservative conference in
Blackpool the possibility of a deal with the rebels which might restrict the
conditions under which BR - as opposed to BR managers - could compete.
When the Lords amendment was first passed in the summer, ministers warned
that it could wreck the whole basis of the planned privatisation - turning
it effectively into a process of compulsory competitive tendering.
With a majority in the Commons ranged against them, that message has been
gradually toned down. One minister said yesterday that the government
remained determined that the arrangements for BR managers to bid should
remain in place but that did not exclude the possibility of separate BR
bids.
One Tory backbench MP said yesterday there were signs the government might
move towards the rebel position. Sir Keith Speed, the rebel leader, had met
ministers during the summer to discuss the way ahead. But Sir Keith, the
usually loyal Conservative MP for Ashford, is to spend conference week in
Qatar, where he is on a parliamentary visit.
