FT  04 OCT 93 / Earthquake aid flown to India
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BOMBAY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDIA received its first foreign shipment of disaster relief aid since
independence in 1947 when a US cargo plane carrying tents and shelter
material touched down at Bombay airport yesterday, Reuter reports from
Bombay. The aircraft also carried US President Bill Clinton's personal
envoy, Mr Ray Flynn, who will assess India's aid needs following Thursday's
earthquake.
Meanwhile, the death toll in the country's worst natural disaster since
independence is probably far less than the 30,000 earlier feared. Police and
rescue workers had estimated the number of dead and missing at 30,000. But
Mr Sharad Pawar, Maharashtra chief minister, put the total number of bodies
recovered so far at 9,349, and officials said the final figure was unlikely
to be much more than double that.
