<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 93 / The Russian Crisis: Battle for survival begins - Wounds of
Moscow confrontation will be deep and lasting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Mr Yegor Gaidar, the first deputy prime minister, appealed last night
for popular support to prevent Russia being turned into 'a giant
concentration camp for decades to come,' he was right to be worried.
Having traded threats with each other, Russia's leaders on either side of
the barricades embarked on a struggle for their own survival.
President Boris Yeltsin, warning that the 'fate of our children is at
stake', last night said his opponents had overstepped all acceptable limits.
He sacked his vice-president, General Alexander Rutskoi, and can be expected
to punish his opponents by the full measure of the law if he wins.
He urged popular support for democracy and market reforms, saying his
opponents would not allow free elections. But he will probably pursue more
oppressive policies at home if he wins the confrontation.
Similarly, Mr Rutskoi said Mr Yeltsin must be held to account for the
collapse of the Soviet Union, of the Russian economy, and of the army.
He vowed to punish corrupt and unpatriotic officials whom he accused of
selling Russia out to western interests. He threatened to try senior
officers who continued to support Mr Yeltsin and expressed his contempt for
most of Russia's mainstream politicians, including former allies such as Mr
Arkady Volsky, the head of the industrialists' union, and his former
ideologue, Mr Vassily Lipitsky.
Mr Rutskoi praised 'patriots' in the National Salvation Front, whose members
have advocated variously a restoration of the Soviet Union, a return to
communism, and a more nationalist foreign policy.
For the former Soviet republics, the issue is one of life-or-death. Having
supported Mr Yeltsin, they could face a return to power of politicians who
want to reconstitute the Soviet Union.
Just as the failed 1991 coup precipitated the collapse of the Soviet Union,
the outcome of this battle could determine whether Russia sticks together as
one country. Russia's provinces, having waited on the sidelines to see which
side would win in Moscow, could be forced to take sides.
With local administrations supporting Mr Yeltsin and the heads of local
councils supporting parliament, there will also be retribution against those
local officials who have backed the losing side.
Despite Mr Yeltsin's appeals for support, the increasing popular
indifference to politics which allowed the president to dissolve parliament
less than two weeks ago could also play against him.
Just like the Russian army, the Russian people are haunted by the memory of
the brutal civil war which ravaged the country seven decades ago. The army,
which has vowed to stay 'neutral' in the current conflict, could begin to
fall apart at the seams if its commanders take sides and if the troops
refuse to obey orders.
The events of the last 24 hours have pushed Russia to the brink of civil
war. If President Yeltsin manages to restore order, the wounds of the
confrontation - due in large part to the folly of politicians - will be deep
and lasting.
</TEXT>
