<DATE>931004
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 93 / Yeltsin acts to quell revolt: 21 die in battles for key
Moscow buildings - Troops and tanks move on capital / Rebels prepare to
defend White House
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW AND AGENCIES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TROOPS with armoured vehicles moved into Moscow streets early today as
President Boris Yeltsin sought to quell the hardline rebellion that brought
fierce gun battles to the city yesterday.
At least 21 people were reported killed and hundreds injured in the
uprising.
With a troop crackdown expected, about 2,000 rebels last night strengthened
barricades around the White House, the parliament building. Others gathered
around the main television centre, which they had earlier attacked and
briefly put off the air before being repulsed in savage fighting with
pro-Yeltsin soldiers from elite units.
Mr Yeltsin, who declared a state of emergency in the capital, vowed he would
triumph over the 'adventurers' backing parliament, which he dissolved in a
decree 12 days previously.
The revolt confronted Mr Yeltsin with an agonising decision he had tried to
avoid in his stand-off with defiant deputies - whether to use force to back
up his decree and clear them and their weapons out of the White House.
As a showdown loomed, Mr Yeltsin's rebellious vice-president, Mr Alexander
Rutskoi, declared an overnight 'curfew' inside parliament. He banned all
movement from floor to floor or along corridors in the darkened building.
Mr Rutskoi, named president by the defiant parliament in the wake of Mr
Yeltsin's decree, yesterday spurred the demonstrators into their violent
actions.
Trouble flared as 15,000 anti-Yeltsin protesters smashed through a security
cordon to link up with deputies at the White House. With passions rising and
guns distributed, demonstrators attacked the mayor's office and raced to the
TV complex, storming inside in a hail of bullets.
Armed supporters of Mr Rutskoi, who was last night dismissed by Mr Yeltsin
from his post as vice-president and from the army, also tried to take over
two Russian news agencies but left without a struggle.
Although gunfire still crackled around the TV centre early today, an
official said: 'For the moment it is quiet.' He said troops arriving in
armoured vehicles were disarming the rebels. Mr Viktor Chernomyrdin, the
prime minister, said in a televised address that troops were being brought
into Moscow to restore order. 'Despite all the difficulties of the
situation, the government is in full control,' he said.
Two divisions of paratroopers loyal to Mr Yeltsin were due to enter Moscow
early today, First Deputy Prime Minister Vladimir Shumeiko said. He said one
division, normally at least 5,000 strong, was coming from the city of
Ryazan, about 110 miles south-east of Moscow.
Mr Strobe Talbott, the US ambassador at large with responsibility for the
former Soviet states, said he had been told by Mr Yeltsin's aides that
troops loyal to the president were taking up positions round parliament and
the TV centre and would retake both 'very shortly'.
Everything seemed to depend on the willingness of the incoming troops to
join battle. After reports that some commanders were wavering in their
loyalty earlier in the day, the Interfax news agency reported late last
night that the chief district commanders, meeting in the praesidium of the
Ministry of Defence, had agreed to back the president. General Pavel
Grachev, the defence minister, was said to be preparing an address to
servicemen - the sympathies of many of whom could be expected to be with the
White House defenders.
However, the determined resis-tance put up against the rebels by the few
troops at the TV centre halted what looked like a serious challenge to
central power.
In the statement read for him on TV, Mr Yeltsin said the attacks had been
'planned in advance' and had been deliberately aimed at destroying
negotiations over the weekend under the aegis of Alexei II, patriarch of the
Russian Orthodox church.
Mr Yeltsin said that 'from different corners of Russia came forces from
pro-communist organisations carrying out their black deeds beneath red
flags. . . Today, the fate of Russia and of our children is being decided.
The forces of civil war will not succeed'. Mr Yegor Gaidar, deputy prime
minister for economic reform, appealed to ordinary citizens to show their
support for democracy at this 'hardest hour'.
'Today we cannot dump responsibility for democracy and our freedom on police
and military forces alone . . . we appeal to you not to allow our country to
be turned into a giant concentration camp for decades to come'.
Mr Chernomyrdin has called Russia's regional leaders to Moscow this
afternoon. The Democratic Russia movement, which held a rally of between
1,000 and 2,000 supporters of the president in central Moscow in the early
evening, appealed for rallies to be held round the country in defence of Mr
Yeltsin.
Reports, Page 2
